The day before the 20th anniversary of Britain&rsquo;s July 1, 1997 handover of Hong Kong to China, China&rsquo;s Ministry of Foreign Affairs admitted to having dispensed with its promises regarding the vibrant city. Beijing called the Sino-British Joint Declaration (SBJD), a 1984 treaty that carefully describes the rights of Hong Kong citizens, a piece of paper that &ldquo;no longer has any practical significance.&rdquo; That is an apparent violation of Article 7 of the treaty, which binds both parties to implement the SBJD in full. The city&rsquo;s Basic Law mini-constitution, which guarantees autonomy for &ldquo;at least 50 years&rdquo; with a policy of &ldquo;one country, two systems&rdquo; and a goal of universal suffrage, has also been abused by pro-Beijing interests.<br />
<br />
According to Michael C. Davis, a long time constitutional law professor at the University of Hong Kong, &ldquo;The SBJD says the Hong Kong courts are to be independent and final. The text of the Basic Law in Article 158 hardly seems to preserve that independence and the way the NPCSC [China&rsquo;s powerful Standing Committee of the National People&rsquo;s Congress] has been behaving lately comes up even shorter. The SBJD says the legislature will be chose[n] by elections with the chief executive appointed on the basis of elections or consultations held locally. Query whether the legislature has even been fully chosen by anything that would pass as elections. Of course the Basic Law promises more and that has not been done either. That the Chinese Government is now disavowing its continued adherence to the Sino-British Joint Declaration can hardly be reassuring to Hong Kong people.&rdquo;

In his increasingly overbearing manner, Xi visited the PLA&rsquo;s hillside garrison in Hong Kong on July 1, rode in an open-air jeep past hundreds of tanks, called for unpopular &ldquo;national security&rdquo; legislation, warned the protesters, and warned the U.S. and U.K., against meddling. &ldquo;Any attempt to endanger China&rsquo;s sovereignty and security, challenge the power of the central government &hellip; or use Hong Kong to carry out infiltration and sabotage against the mainland, is an act that crosses the red line and is absolutely impermissible,&rdquo; said Xi at the inauguration of Carrie Lam, the city&rsquo;s new chief executive. Lam is, as one might expect since Xi attended her inauguration, soft on China.<br />
<br />
In what is perhaps a show of force masked as part of the &ldquo;celebrations,&rdquo; China&rsquo;s first aircraft carrier, the Liaoning, was en route to Hong Kong on July 2 through the Taiwan Strait. But when it docks there will not be the families flying in, and friendly bar hopping, that characterize the visits of other navies. Chinese sailors are prohibited from most interaction with locals. China&rsquo;s Interior Service Regulations state, &ldquo;When interacting with foreigners, soldiers should strictly act according to the related regulations and unauthorised interaction is not allowed. Soldiers shall not engage in improper and unnecessary communication with local staff and shall not participate in unhealthy consumer entertainment.&rdquo;
